	  <exercise>
		    <caption>Describing linear motions</caption>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Find the expression which describes the linear motion of a particle which moves as follows</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>It is in position <math>
                        <latex>(4,1,4)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>, and in position <math>
                        <latex>(12,2,-6)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,1,4) + t\cdot (8,1,-10)</latex>
                           </math>, where <math>
                              <latex>t</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Try fitting the information given into the equation for a linear motion</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.display>
						            <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = \mathbf{a} + t\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
					          </math.display>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <caption>Purely formal approach</caption>
               <solution.body>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>From the statement of the problem we know two facts:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							\begin{array}{rccclcll}
							\mathbf{l}(0) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 0\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} &amp; = &amp; (4,1,4) &amp; (I) \\
							\mathbf{l}(1) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 1\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp; (12,2,-6) &amp; (II)
							\end{array}
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>From (I), we know that <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{a} = (4,1,4)</latex>
                        </math>. Substituting this into (II), we find:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\mathbf{v} = (12,2,-6) - (4,1,4) = (8,1,-10)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, the expression which describes the motion of the particle is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,1,4) + t\cdot (8,1,-10)</latex>
                        </math>, where <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
			      <approach version="2">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,1,4) + t\cdot (8,1,-10)</latex>
                           </math>, where <math>
                              <latex>t</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <caption>Direct by inspection</caption>
               <solution.body>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We are given the information that the particle passes through <math>
                           <latex>(4,1,4)</latex>
                        </math> at time <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{0}</latex>
                        </math>. Moreover, the particle travels from <math>
                           <latex>(4,1,4)</latex>
                        </math> to <math>
                           <latex>(12,2,-6)</latex>
                        </math> in a period of one time unit. Therefore</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							\mathbf{v} = (12,2,-6) - (4,1,4) = (8,1,-10)
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, the expression which describes the motion of the particle is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,1,4) + t\cdot (8,1,-10)</latex>
                        </math>, where <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>It is in position <math>
                        <latex>(1,6)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>, and in position <math>
                        <latex>(-2,4)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,8) + t\cdot (-3,-2)</latex>
                           </math>, where <math>
                              <latex>t</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Try fitting the information given into the equation for a linear motion</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.display>
						            <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = \mathbf{a} + t\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
					          </math.display>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>From the statement of the problem we know two facts:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							\begin{array}{rcccrl}
							\mathbf{l}(1) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 1\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp;  (1,6) &amp; (I) \\
							\mathbf{l}(2) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 2\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp;  (-2,4) &amp; (II)
							\end{array}
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We are looking for those vectors <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v}</latex>
                        </math> which solve both equations simultaneously. By forming <math>
                           <latex>(II) - (I)</latex>
                        </math>, we find:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\mathbf{l}(2) - \mathbf{l}(1) = \mathbf{v} = (-2,4) - (1,6) = (-3,-2)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Substituting <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v} = (-3,-2)</latex>
                        </math> into equation <math>
                           <latex>(I)</latex>
                        </math>, we get:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\mathbf{a} = (1,6) - (-3,-2) = (4,8)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, the expression which describes the motion of the particle is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (4,8) + t\cdot (-3,-2)</latex>
                        </math>, where <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>It is in position <math>
                        <latex>(1,1,1)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math>, and in position <math>
                        <latex>(17,-3,13)</latex>
                     </math> at time <math>
                        <latex>7</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (-11,4,-8) + t\cdot (4,-1,3)</latex>
                           </math>, where <math>
                              <latex>t</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>From the statement of the problem we know two facts:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							\begin{array}{rcccrl}
							\mathbf{l}(3) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 3\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; =  &amp; (1,1,1) &amp; (I) \\
							\mathbf{l}(7) &amp; = &amp; \mathbf{a} + 7\cdot \mathbf{v} &amp; = &amp;  (17,-3,13) &amp; (II)
							\end{array}
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We are looking for those vectors <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v}</latex>
                        </math> which solve both equations simultaneously. By forming <math>
                           <latex>(II) - (I)</latex>
                        </math>, we find:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\mathbf{l}(7) - \mathbf{l}(3) = 4\cdot \mathbf{v} = (16,-4,12)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v} = (4,-1,3)</latex>
                        </math>. Substituting <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v} = (4,-1,3)</latex>
                        </math> into equation <math>
                           <latex>(I)</latex>
                        </math>, we get:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\mathbf{a} = (1,1,1) - 3\cdot (4,-1,3) = (-11,4,-8)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, the expression which describes the motion of the particle is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (-11,4,-8) + t\cdot (4,-1,3)</latex>
                        </math>, where <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Two particles move according to the equations</para.body>
            </para>
			         <para align="center">
               <para.body>
				              <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}_1 = (3,1,-1) + t\cdot (4,0,6)</latex>
                  </math>  and  <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}_2 = (4,3,1) + t\cdot (2,0,2)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Determine whether the particles collide or not. If they do, where? and when?</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>The two paths do not cross. Therefore the particles do not collide.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The two particles collide exactly when there is a time <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> for which  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}_1(t) = \mathbf{l}_2(t)</latex>
                        </math>. Accordingly, we look for a solution of the vector equation</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							\aligned
							(3,1,-1) + t\cdot (4,0,6) &amp; = &amp; (4,3,1) + t\cdot (2,0,2) \\
							t\cdot \left( (4,0,6) - (2,0,2)\right) &amp; = &amp; (4,3,1) - (3,1,-1) \\
							t\cdot (2,0,4) &amp; = &amp; (1,2,2)
							\endaligned
							
							</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Consider the second coordinate of the bottom line: it requires of a number <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> that <math>
                           <latex>t\cdot 0 = 2</latex>
                        </math>, which is impossible. Therefore the two particles do not collide.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Determine whether the paths of the particles cross each other. If the do, where?</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The paths of the two particles cross each other exactly when there is a time <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> and a time <math>
                           <latex>s</latex>
                        </math>   for which <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{l}_1(t) = \mathbf{l}_2(s)</latex>
                        </math>. Accordingly, we look for a solution of the vector equation</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							\aligned
							(3,1,-1) + t\cdot (4,0,6) &amp; =  (4,3,1) + s\cdot (2,0,2) \\
							-s\cdot (2,0,2) + t\cdot (4,0,6) &amp; = (4,3,1) - (3,1,-1) = (1,2,-1)  
							\endaligned
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Inspection of the second coordinate shows that a valid solution consists of numbers <math>
                           <latex>s</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> with <math>
                           <latex>s\cdot 0 + t\cdot 0 = 2</latex>
                        </math>. No such numbers <math>
                           <latex>s</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> exist. Therefore the paths of the two particles do not cross.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>A particle is traveling according to the equation</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = (1,0,1) + t\cdot (2,4,-1)</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Determine the velocity of a missile that is fired from <math>
                     <latex>(4,4,4)</latex>
                  </math> at time <math>
                     <latex>2</latex>
                  </math> and travels linearly so that it hits the particle at time <math>
                     <latex>10</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <answer.exercise>
            <answer.exercise.block>
               <answer.exercise.block.body>
				              <para>
                     <para.body>The velocity vector of the missile is  <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v} = (17,36,-13)/8</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
			            </answer.exercise.block.body>
            </answer.exercise.block>
         </answer.exercise>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>First find the location of the particle at the time of the impact.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>Next determine the vector from the starting point of the missile to the impact point. - How is this vector related to the velocity vector of the missile?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>At the instant of colission the particle is in position</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>\mathbf{l}(10) = (1,0,1) + 10\cdot (2,4,-1) = (21,40,-9)</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the vector describing the displacement of the missile between time <math>
                        <latex>t=2</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>t=10</latex>
                     </math> is</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>\mathbf{T} = (21,40,-9) - (4,4,4) = (17,36,-13)</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the velocity vector of the missile is  <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{v} = \frac{1}{8}\cdot (17,36,-13)</latex>
                     </math>. This answers the problem. In addition, we can now write down the equation for the linear motion of the missile:</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para align="center">
                  <para.body>
					                <subordinate>
                        <hot>
							                    <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{m}(t) = (4,4,4) + \dfrac{(t-2)}{8}\cdot (17,36,-13)</latex>
                           </math>
						                  </hot>
                        <info>
							                    <para>
                              <para.body>We subtract <math>
                                    <latex>2</latex>
                                 </math> from <math>
                                    <latex>t</latex>
                                 </math>, because the missile starts from <math>
                                    <latex>(4,4,4)</latex>
                                 </math> at time <math>
                                    <latex>t=2</latex>
                                 </math>. – So <math>
                                    <latex>\mathbf{m}(2) = (4,4,4)</latex>
                                 </math>, and this is exactly what this linear motion describes.</para.body>
                           </para>
						                  </info>
                     </subordinate>
				              </para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Consider the linear motion in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>\Vect{l}(t) = \Vect{a}\ +\ t\cdot \Vect{v}</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>with <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>. Show that the motion passes through the origin if and only if <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                  </math> is parallel to <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>There are two inferences you need to verify:</para.body>
            </para>
				        <ul>
					          <li>
						            <para>
                     <para.body>If the motion passes through the origin, then <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                        </math> is parallel to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
					          </li>
					          <li>
						            <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                        </math> is parallel to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                        </math>, then the motion passes through the origin.</para.body>
                  </para>
					          </li>
				        </ul>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The motion passes through the origin if and only if the vector equation</para.body>
            </para>
				        <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a} + t\cdot \Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
				        <para>
               <para.body>has a solution.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
</exercise.pack>
